{{for|films named ''Heist''|Heist (disambiguation)#Film}} The '''heist film''' or '''caper film'''<ref name="hardy">{{cite book | editor-last=Hardy | editor-first=Phil | year=1997 | chapter=The Caper Film | title=The BFI Companion to Crime | publisher=[[A & C Black]] | pages=70–71 | isbn=978-0-304-33215-1 }}</ref> is a [[subgenre]] of [[crime film]]. It focuses on the planning, execution, and aftermath of a [[theft]]. They could be described as the analogues of [[caper story|caper stories]] in [[history of film|film history]]. A typical film includes many [[plot twist]]s, with the focus on the characters' attempts to formulate a plan, carry it out, and escape with the goods. Often a [[Archenemy|nemesis]] must be thwarted, who might be either a figure of authority or else a former partner who turned on the group or one of its members.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
